00:45:59.042 --> 00:46:01.250
AUDIENCE: In all of the
submissions that you received

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:03.840
for "What If," were there
ever any that intrigued you,

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:05.700
but that were just
too frightening.

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:08.700
You weren't going to touch
them with a 10-foot pole?

00:46:08.700 --> 00:46:11.570
RANDALL MUNROE: Yeah, there have
been a number of weird things.

00:46:14.110 --> 00:46:17.650
I had one person
who in their job

00:46:17.650 --> 00:46:25.640
may have conceivably-- they
asked a question about-- a fun

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:28.700
earth science question
involving nuclear weapons.

00:46:28.700 --> 00:46:36.730
And their from address, the
TLD that it was coming from,

00:46:36.730 --> 00:46:40.087
and the title that was
after their signature,

00:46:40.087 --> 00:46:42.170
and then some of what they
described in the letter

00:46:42.170 --> 00:46:44.050
suggested that perhaps
this was a person who

00:46:44.050 --> 00:46:47.630
had access to nuclear weapons.

00:46:47.630 --> 00:46:53.720
And that was a little worrying.

00:46:53.720 --> 00:46:56.570
I have also gotten
ones from-- I had one

00:46:56.570 --> 00:46:59.070
that I think came from
a doctor that was like,

00:46:59.070 --> 00:47:01.780
suppose that a toxin blocks
the effect of so and so

00:47:01.780 --> 00:47:04.175
on a patient's so
and so receptors,

00:47:04.175 --> 00:47:05.800
and it was delivered
at this dose, what

00:47:05.800 --> 00:47:08.765
would be the effect
of this toxin?

00:47:08.765 --> 00:47:11.390
And that's not sort of the vibe
of the usual "What If" question

00:47:11.390 --> 00:47:11.890
I get.

00:47:11.890 --> 00:47:19.140
And it gave me the sense
that somewhere there's

00:47:19.140 --> 00:47:24.070
a doctor who's in a
hospital at a computer,

00:47:24.070 --> 00:47:28.770
and there's a nurse coming in
who's like, Doctor, Doctor!

00:47:28.770 --> 00:47:31.764
Asking her, we have
a patient so and so.

00:47:31.764 --> 00:47:32.680
What is your decision?

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:33.721
What are you going to do?

00:47:33.721 --> 00:47:36.370
They have this talk, and
the doctor's like, hang on.

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:39.520
There's an internet
cartoonist who I really

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:40.850
think we should ask about this.

00:47:40.850 --> 00:47:43.209
And they're waiting
for-- like, we

00:47:43.209 --> 00:47:44.750
have to wait for
this week's article.

00:47:44.750 --> 00:47:47.470
But hopefully you'll
tackle this for us.

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:52.169
And so that's definitely
sort of worrying.

00:47:52.169 --> 00:47:54.460
I also get a lot of questions
that are very transparent

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:56.270
attempts to get me to
do people's homework.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:59.390
Like, what if you had a ball
was on an inclined plane

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:02.550
at this many degrees that was
this many centimeters long,

00:48:02.550 --> 00:48:03.300
and you let it go?

00:48:03.300 --> 00:48:04.510
Like, how many
seconds do you think

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:05.843
it would take to hit the bottom?

00:48:08.130 --> 00:48:11.710
It's like, nice try.

00:48:11.710 --> 00:48:16.770
And then I think, actually,
the most worrying ones

00:48:16.770 --> 00:48:19.870
are-- there are a
bunch where they're

00:48:19.870 --> 00:48:26.550
totally reasonable, legitimate,
answerable questions that I

00:48:26.550 --> 00:48:30.260
still just refuse to tackle.

00:48:30.260 --> 00:48:34.540
Which are like-- one of them
was someone asked would it

00:48:34.540 --> 00:48:38.840
be possible to chill your
teeth to such a low temperature

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:41.266
that drinking a cup of hot
coffee would cause them

00:48:41.266 --> 00:48:41.765
to shatter?

00:48:46.470 --> 00:48:53.230
And I included this
question, and I have never

00:48:53.230 --> 00:48:57.370
been able to get beyond
the end of that sentence

00:48:57.370 --> 00:49:02.320
without just cringing,
because I imagine it.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:04.340
And so I have never-- I
don't have the stomach

00:49:04.340 --> 00:49:06.761
to do the research to
answer that question.

00:49:06.761 --> 00:49:08.260
And so there are a
couple like that,

00:49:08.260 --> 00:49:10.790
where it's like this
is just pushing it.

00:49:13.540 --> 00:49:17.970
But other than that, there's
a huge number of what

00:49:17.970 --> 00:49:20.330
if Superhero X
fought Superhero Y.

00:49:20.330 --> 00:49:23.916
And I feel like that's
A, sort of hard to answer

00:49:23.916 --> 00:49:26.290
scientifically, because the
powers of the superheros sort

00:49:26.290 --> 00:49:28.040
of change depending
on who's writing them,

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:31.470
and it will often be the ones
who are sort of infinitely

00:49:31.470 --> 00:49:33.530
powerful, where it's
not really well-defined

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:36.040
what the limits of
their powers are.

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:38.120
But I've gotten to learn
a great list of all

00:49:38.120 --> 00:49:41.204
of the near-infinite
power superheroes,

00:49:41.204 --> 00:49:43.620
because people really like to
pit them against each other.

00:49:43.620 --> 00:49:48.940
And part way I don't
answer that is that,

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:51.190
in addition to being hard
to tackle with science,

00:49:51.190 --> 00:49:56.157
it's-- from what I understand--
that's basically the kind

00:49:56.157 --> 00:49:58.490
of question that superhero
comics exist to try to answer

00:49:58.490 --> 00:49:59.190
in the first place.

00:49:59.190 --> 00:50:01.363
It's like, what if we took
Hero X from mythology X

00:50:01.363 --> 00:50:05.770
and had crossover with
someone from mythology y.

00:50:05.770 --> 00:50:08.930
And I was thinking that this--
but this interest in asking

00:50:08.930 --> 00:50:12.340
about infinity is
a common trend,

00:50:12.340 --> 00:50:15.910
and it's not limited
to just superheroes,

00:50:15.910 --> 00:50:18.760
because before that it's
exactly the same impulse that

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:23.870
leads people to ask the
old question of could God

00:50:23.870 --> 00:50:26.170
make a rock so heavy
that he can't lift it?

00:50:26.170 --> 00:50:31.422
And this question--
you've defined this person

00:50:31.422 --> 00:50:32.380
as infinitely powerful.

00:50:32.380 --> 00:50:34.860
How powerful are they really?

00:50:34.860 --> 00:50:38.050
Goku from "Dragon Ball Z"
I gather, at some point

00:50:38.050 --> 00:50:39.930
becomes nearly
infinitely powerful,

00:50:39.930 --> 00:50:41.888
because people keep asking
questions about what

00:50:41.888 --> 00:50:43.714
if he fought the
Hulk or Superman?

00:50:43.714 --> 00:50:45.630
And so I think this is
sort of a common trend,

00:50:45.630 --> 00:50:50.860
although I was thinking
that I don't think anyone

00:50:50.860 --> 00:50:53.930
has-- this has been a common
trend throughout history--

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:57.060
but I don't know if they
necessarily always combine them

00:50:57.060 --> 00:50:59.510
with the sort of pitting
rivals, because I

00:50:59.510 --> 00:51:01.150
don't think anyone
who's ever asked in.

00:51:01.150 --> 00:51:02.950
What if Goku "Dragon
Ball Z" fought

00:51:02.950 --> 00:51:04.430
the God of the Old Testament?

00:51:08.554 --> 00:51:10.720
And I don't know what science
has to say about that,

00:51:10.720 --> 00:51:11.740
but if anyone does
discover if they've

00:51:11.740 --> 00:51:13.864
done a crossover comic of
that, please let me know.

00:51:13.864 --> 00:51:14.780
I would read that.

