to ask you questions.

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:29.470
I was wondering how many
of those do you get,

00:54:29.470 --> 00:54:30.880
and how do you
whittle them down?

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:32.510
And really what I
would like to know

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:34.377
is how do I ask you
the perfect question

00:54:34.377 --> 00:54:35.460
that you end up answering?

00:54:38.262 --> 00:54:39.470
RANDALL MUNROE: I don't know.

00:54:39.470 --> 00:54:47.184
So it's really nice to that
so many of you came out here.

00:54:47.184 --> 00:54:48.600
Although I feel
like that's easier

00:54:48.600 --> 00:54:51.240
to do when it's appearing at a
workplace, because it's like,

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:52.680
so do I work on
the thing that I'm

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:55.070
supposed to do
this evening, or go

00:54:55.070 --> 00:54:56.725
hang out of the
talk about comics?

00:55:00.150 --> 00:55:04.630
I'm flattered, but I figure--

00:55:04.630 --> 00:55:07.090
But there are definitely a
lot of questions submitted,

00:55:07.090 --> 00:55:11.950
and I will admit to doing--
there's some sort of filters

00:55:11.950 --> 00:55:12.950
that I put on the inbox.

00:55:12.950 --> 00:55:15.609
So after a little bit
I started filtering out

00:55:15.609 --> 00:55:17.650
the names of all of the
invulnerable superheroes,

00:55:17.650 --> 00:55:20.800
because they were just too
many questions about them that

00:55:20.800 --> 00:55:25.680
were never ones that I was
going to be able to answer.

00:55:25.680 --> 00:55:32.080
I also filtered out the word
"woodchuck" after week one.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:35.190
Because the first time
someone submitted "hey,

00:55:35.190 --> 00:55:37.180
how much would could a
woodchuck really chuck

00:55:37.180 --> 00:55:39.450
if a woodchuck
could chuck wood?"

00:55:39.450 --> 00:55:39.950
I laughed.

00:55:39.950 --> 00:55:40.922
I was like that's
funny, and then

00:55:40.922 --> 00:55:42.900
the second time I was like,
oh, yeah, hey, someone else

00:55:42.900 --> 00:55:43.775
thought of that joke.

00:55:43.775 --> 00:55:48.800
And then in the first week it
was like 70 or 80 emails that

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:50.440
were just the same
woodchuck joke,

00:55:50.440 --> 00:55:53.980
and then by then I was like,
OK, I now hate that rhyme,

00:55:53.980 --> 00:55:56.030
and I refuse to
answer any questions

00:55:56.030 --> 00:55:58.920
about woodchucks on principle.

00:55:58.920 --> 00:56:03.140
But other than that,
I actually find

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:07.100
some of my favorite questions
come from little kids,

00:56:07.100 --> 00:56:12.180
because adults will sort of try
to be really clever about it

00:56:12.180 --> 00:56:14.230
and come up with a
question that suggests all

00:56:14.230 --> 00:56:16.220
these horrible
consequences, and they've

00:56:16.220 --> 00:56:20.410
set up a scenario that's going
to result in a mushroom cloud

00:56:20.410 --> 00:56:22.280
engulfing wherever it
is you're doing this.

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:24.530
Whereas little kids will ask
extremely straightforward

00:56:24.530 --> 00:56:26.905
questions like, I want to
build a billion-story building.

00:56:26.905 --> 00:56:28.140
Can I do that?

00:56:28.140 --> 00:56:32.700
And then answering
takes you in a bunch

00:56:32.700 --> 00:56:35.330
of unexpected directions.

00:56:35.330 --> 00:56:38.330
So my advice to people who
are submitting questions

00:56:38.330 --> 00:56:41.330
is mostly ask little
kids for questions,

00:56:41.330 --> 00:56:43.732
because they have
some of the best ones.

00:56:43.732 --> 00:56:44.815
AUDIENCE: Cool, thank you.

00:56:44.815 --> 00:56:46.148
RANDALL MUNROE: Yeah, thank you.

